  "local_port": 49154,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you choose an unresponsive yoyo?",
  "response": "Choosing an unresponsive yoyo involves considering several factors to ensure that it fits your playing style and preferences. Here are some key points to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Skill Level**: Unresponsive yoyos are generally recommended for intermediate to advanced players who are comfortable with tricks that require a return to the hand after a throw, such as binds. If you're still a beginner, you may want to start with a responsive yoyo.\n\n2. **Yoyo Shape**: Different yoyo shapes (e.g., butterfly, straight, organic) affect performance and playability. Butterfly shapes provide more space for string tricks, while organic shapes can offer a more comfortable feel for casual play.\n\n3. **Material**: Unresponsive yoyos are typically made from aluminum or plastic. Aluminum yoyos are generally more durable and offer better spin times, while plastic yoyos can be more affordable and may provide a different feel during play.\n\n4. **Weight and Diameter**: Heavier unresponsive yoyos tend to spin longer but may feel slower. Lighter yoyos can be more agile and easier to manipulate but may require more skill for stable play. Diameter also affects how the yoyo handles and how easy it is to catch on the string.\n\n5. **Response System**: Unresponsive yoyos typically use a silicone response system or pads. Consider the type of response system it has, as this will impact how it binds and how easy it is to return to your hand.\n\n6. **Bearing Size**: The size of the yoyo bearing affects its spin time and responsiveness. Larger bearings (like size C) often provide longer spin times and better stability.\n\n7. **Design and Aesthetics**: Choose a design that appeals to you visually. Many manufacturers offer a variety of colors and finishes.\n\n8. **Brand Reputation**: Research different brands and read reviews from other players. Some brands are well-known for their quality and performance, such as YoYoFactory, Duncan, and CLYW.\n\n9. **Budget**: Decide how much you\u2019re willing to spend. Unresponsive yoyos come in a range of prices, so set a budget that suits your needs.\n\n10. **Try Before You Buy**: If possible, try out different yoyos at a local yoyo club or store. Personal feel and playability are crucial and can vary greatly between models.\n\nBy considering these factors, you'll be better equipped to choose an unresponsive yoyo that matches your style and helps you progress in your yoyoing skills.",
